type="local"
addr="leonipugh">Leoni Pugh</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00RN</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>\alpha</fr:tex> be an “action”, and consider the two processes <fr:tex>\alpha \star</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>\alpha . \varnothing  +  \alpha \star</fr:tex>.</fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause><fr:p>We have <fr:tex>\mathbf {Traces} { \mathopen {} \left ( \alpha \star \right ) \mathclose {}}  =  { \mathopen {} \left \{ \varepsilon ,  \alpha ,  \alpha . \alpha , \ldots \right \} \mathclose {}} = \mathbf {Traces} { \mathopen {} \left ( \alpha . \varnothing  +  \alpha \star \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>.</fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause><fr:p>But the process <fr:tex>\alpha \star</fr:tex> can never get stuck, whereas <fr:tex>\alpha . \varnothing  +  \alpha \star</fr:tex> gets stuck if it proceeds along the left branch.</fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause><fr:p>Thus trace equivalence is highly un-physical. To deal with this, we generalise the information <fr:em>order</fr:em> to a category in which bisimulation can be expressed. <fr:strong>Idea: non-determinism must be modelled by a <fr:em>van Kampen</fr:em> colimit (e.g. disjoint coproduct).</fr:strong></fr:p><fr:p>See <fr:link
href="joyal-nielsen-winskel-1996.xml"
type="local"
addr="joyal-nielsen-winskel-1996">Joyal, Nielsen and Winskel (1996)</fr:link> and <fr:link
href="cattani-winskel-2005.xml"
type="local"
addr="cattani-winskel-2005">Cattani and Winskel (2005)</fr:link>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:backlinks><fr:references></fr:references></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>